  "prompt": "What is the minimum level of mathematical proficiency required to graduate from West Point?",
  "response": "Graduates of West Point are required to demonstrate proficiency in a range of mathematical concepts. The specific courses and their content might evolve, but generally, the minimum level of mathematical proficiency needed to graduate includes:\n\n*   **Calculus:** A solid understanding of single-variable calculus, including limits, derivatives, integrals, and applications of these concepts. This is typically covered in Calculus I and often Calculus II.\n\n*   **Differential Equations:** Basic concepts of Ordinary Differential Equations. This may be a separate course or part of a combined calculus/differential equations sequence.\n\n*   **Linear Algebra:** Understanding of vectors, matrices, linear transformations, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors.\n\n*   **Probability and Statistics:** Basic probability concepts, descriptive statistics, hypothesis testing, and statistical inference.\n\n*   **Discrete Mathematics:** Logic, set theory, graph theory, and basic proof techniques may be included, often as part of the computer science curriculum.\n\nIn summary, a minimum requirement is a solid grounding in calculus (at least through Calculus I), linear algebra, probability and statistics. However, most cadets will take more advanced math courses depending on their major.\n\nIt's important to note:\n*   The precise course requirements and content can change.\n*   The level of understanding required goes beyond memorizing formulas; cadets need to apply these concepts to solve real-world problems in engineering, science, and military contexts.\n*   Cadets are also expected to use computational tools (like MATLAB or Python) to solve mathematical problems.",
